# Database Wire-Protocol Rules

Read these before changing protocol code:

- `docs/rules/database-protocol-rules.md`
- `docs/rules/ai-error-handling-rules.md`

Hard rules:

- Treat every database protocol as an explicit state machine.
- Implement protocol frame/message codecs before command handlers.
- Validate frame length, endian, message type, command type, sequence id, and
  legal state transition before mutating session state.
- Keep startup, capability negotiation, authentication, query execution,
  streaming, cancellation, and termination as separate protocol phases.
- Do not log plaintext passwords, auth responses, SCRAM proof, salts, tokens, or
  credential-bearing URLs.
- Do not hand-build wire packets with ad hoc string concatenation.
- Do not parse PostgreSQL StartupMessage as a normal typed message.
- Do not parse MySQL SSLRequest as a normal Handshake Response.
- Do not implement a future database protocol by returning the MySQL or
  PostgreSQL adapter as a placeholder.
- Add or update tests before changing frame, startup, handshake, auth, command,
  result, transaction-state, or error behavior.
- On compile, test, runtime, protocol-spec, or user-feedback failures, follow
  `docs/rules/ai-error-handling-rules.md`: classify, find root cause, fix one
  cause, verify narrow-to-wide, and update rules/tests when a gap is found.

Current first-phase scope:

- MySQL: packet header, little-endian primitives, length-encoded values,
  Connection Phase, HandshakeV10, SSLRequest handling, authentication exchange,
  Command Phase, COM_QUERY, COM_INIT_DB, COM_QUIT, COM_PING, OK/ERR/EOF,
  text resultset, status flags, SQLSTATE mapping.
- PostgreSQL: untyped startup messages, big-endian typed messages, SSLRequest,
  StartupMessage, authentication cycle, ParameterStatus, BackendKeyData,
  ReadyForQuery transaction status, Simple Query, Extended Query skeleton,
  ErrorResponse/NoticeResponse, RowDescription/DataRow, CommandComplete, Sync
  error recovery.
